⭐ Rules

Just like your previous projects:

Use guard clauses whenever possible.
Don't make variables public.
Change the object's state correctly (isLoggedIn, item count, etc.).
Keep methods focused on one responsibility.
Use comments if they help you understand your own code.
📝 Your challenge

This time, I want you to design a little more on your own. In the last few projects, you often asked, "What should happen here?" That's normal, but now you're ready to make some decisions yourself.

For example, ask yourself:

Should viewCart() require the user to be logged in, or should anyone be able to view it?
Should logout() automatically clear the cart, or should the cart stay the same?
Should a Platinum member behave differently from a Silver member right now, or is it enough just to store the membership level?

There isn't always one "correct" answer. Part of becoming a good programmer is making reasonable design decisions and being able to explain why you chose them.

Once you've finished it, send me all three classes and your Main class, and I'll mark it like a real coding assessment—looking at correctness, OOP design, readability, and whether you're thinking like a Java developer rather than just writing code.